# Git Commit Generation Protocol

When asked to generate a commit message or when the user types "commit" or "сделай коммит":

## 1. Information Gathering (Mandatory)
1. Run `git status` to see what is staged/unstaged.
2. Run `git diff --cached` to see the exact code changes.
3. If changes touch files with `@skill` references or `.mdc` rules, read those skills/rules via MCP first.

## 2. Commit Message Format
```
<type>(<scope>): <short summary in English>

<optional body: what changed and why, max 72 chars per line>

[Skill: <skill-id>]   (if a skill was applied, created, or modified)
[SSOT: <filename>]    (if paths.js, .env.example, or package.json changed)
[Rule: <rule-file>]   (if a .cursor/rules/*.mdc was added or modified)
```

**Types**: `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `chore`, `docs`, `test`, `build`

## 3. Hard Rules
- Commit message body and footer MUST be in English.
- NEVER commit without an explicit user instruction — generate the message and wait for approval.
- NEVER use `--no-verify` or skip hooks unless user explicitly requests it.
- After commit: run `npm run health-check` and report the result.
